00:19.800 --> 00:23.300
- From the Pen & Teller theater
in Las Vegas, Nevada,

00:23.300 --> 00:27.030
here's our host,
Alyson Hannigan.

00:27.030 --> 00:30.030
[cheers and applause]

00:39.829 --> 00:42.729
- Welcome to
"Penn & Teller: Fool Us."

00:42.729 --> 00:44.200
Tonight, you have a choice.

00:44.200 --> 00:46.500
We can watch
an unrated director's cut

00:46.500 --> 00:50.469
of my 1988 movie,
"My Stepmother Is an Alien."

00:50.469 --> 00:53.630
Or we can watch the show where
the world's best magicians

00:53.630 --> 00:57.229
get a chance to win a shot
performing in Penn and Teller's

00:57.229 --> 00:59.700
amazing Las Vegas show.

00:59.700 --> 01:02.469
Okay!
[cheers and applause]

01:02.469 --> 01:04.400
Magic show it is.

01:04.400 --> 01:06.400
And what better way
to start a magic show

01:06.400 --> 01:10.299
than bringing out two of the
greatest magicians of all time--

01:10.299 --> 01:12.370
Penn and Teller!

01:12.370 --> 01:15.370
[cheers and applause]

01:21.930 --> 01:24.329
Take a seat, gentlemen.

01:24.329 --> 01:25.700
- How you doin'?

01:29.599 --> 01:31.769
- Here comes
our first magician.

01:31.769 --> 01:34.400
Teller, you think I'm bluffing?
I'm not.

01:34.400 --> 01:35.400
Take a look.

01:37.829 --> 01:39.770
- My name is Anthony Asimov,

01:39.770 --> 01:41.930
and I'm what they call
a prop magician.

01:41.930 --> 01:45.670
I did magic for corporations,
for private parties for years,

01:45.670 --> 01:48.569
but I just felt another
creative calling coming,

01:48.569 --> 01:49.969
and so I left magic.

01:49.969 --> 01:52.629
It was sort of like
a coming-out to my family.

01:52.629 --> 01:54.370
I'm like, "I'm leaving magic."

01:54.370 --> 01:55.500
Aah!

01:55.500 --> 01:57.069
My second love
is horror movies,

01:57.069 --> 01:59.069
and so I moved to L.A.
and became a producer,

01:59.069 --> 02:01.170
but every couple years,
I'd take out the cards,

02:01.170 --> 02:03.670
and the last time it happened,
I had a lot of fun.

02:03.670 --> 02:05.700
Now after leaving magic
for 12 years

02:05.700 --> 02:08.370
and having a different
perspective, just from age,

02:08.370 --> 02:09.930
I would have to say I'm better.

02:09.930 --> 02:11.870
Now that I have a really nice
balance of magic and horror,

02:11.870 --> 02:13.500
it's kind of, like, my life.

02:13.500 --> 02:15.530
If I'm not doing magic, I'm
doing horror, and vice versa.

02:17.800 --> 02:19.729
[cheers and applause]

02:19.729 --> 02:22.099
- This next magician
is from Jersey,

02:22.099 --> 02:25.170
so if you think he's intimidated
by Penn and Teller,

02:25.170 --> 02:26.930
forget about it.
[laughter]

02:26.930 --> 02:31.170
Here with two randomly selected
members of our studio audience,

02:31.170 --> 02:34.629
please welcome Anthony Asimov.

02:34.629 --> 02:36.569
[cheers and applause]

02:36.569 --> 02:38.670
- I love a packed house!

02:38.670 --> 02:41.930
My name is Anthony Asimov,
and when you see me do

02:41.930 --> 02:43.229
what I'm about to do,

02:43.229 --> 02:46.400
you're gonna say that was crazy,
that was nuts.

02:46.400 --> 02:47.969
I was there, I saw him do it,

02:47.969 --> 02:50.629
and I don't know how he did it.
Shall we begin?

02:50.629 --> 02:52.430
both: Yes.

02:55.030 --> 02:57.199
- That's nuts.
[laughter]

02:57.199 --> 02:59.670
Sir, miss, does that look like
a bowl of walnuts to you?

02:59.670 --> 03:01.129
both: Yes.
- A big round of applause

03:01.129 --> 03:03.729
for our very observant
spectators.

03:03.729 --> 03:06.530
[applause]

03:06.530 --> 03:08.530
I'm trying to get these cards
out of my hands.

03:08.530 --> 03:11.129
The less I do with them,
the better, okay?

03:11.129 --> 03:12.800
But for now, I'd just like
you to confirm

03:12.800 --> 03:15.870
that they are different and
in no particular order, correct?

03:15.870 --> 03:17.430
- Yes.
- Yes, right here, different.

03:17.430 --> 03:19.569
Well-mixed, and
in no particular order, correct?

03:19.569 --> 03:21.099
- Yeah.

03:21.099 --> 03:24.099
- The reason I'm trying to get
these cards out of my hand,

03:24.099 --> 03:26.870
is because when
magicians touch the cards,

03:26.870 --> 03:29.599
they do that thing
called sleight of hand.

03:29.599 --> 03:31.569
You've heard that before, right?
- Yes.

03:31.569 --> 03:33.770
- Right, well, I'm not gonna
do any sleight of hand

03:33.770 --> 03:36.270
with any of these cards.

03:36.270 --> 03:38.900
Mr. Jillette, if you could
please name any number

03:38.900 --> 03:42.900
between 1 and 52,
and I will count to that card.

03:42.900 --> 03:45.670
What number would you like, sir?
- Let's make it 12.

03:45.670 --> 03:47.670
- 12. 12 it is.

03:47.670 --> 03:49.670
Now from the top of the deck,
okay,

03:49.670 --> 03:50.870
and you, please keep me honest.

03:50.870 --> 03:53.229
One, two, three, four five,

03:53.229 --> 03:56.000
six, seven, eight, nine, ten,
eleven, twelve.

03:56.000 --> 03:57.170
Correct?
- Yes.

03:57.170 --> 03:59.530
- And we have the 4 of diamonds.

03:59.530 --> 04:01.000
Now I just have to check.

04:01.000 --> 04:03.270
If you had continued counting,
we would have selected

04:03.270 --> 04:04.669
one of these cards,
and these are--

04:04.669 --> 04:06.629
none of these are
the 4 of diamonds, correct?

04:06.629 --> 04:08.930
Any of these cards, correct?
- Mm-hmm.

04:08.930 --> 04:13.169
- But no, Mr. Jillette,
you selected the 4 of diamonds.

04:13.169 --> 04:15.069
It's time to bring out
my assistant.

04:15.069 --> 04:20.170
All I ask is the audience
do not be afraid.

04:20.170 --> 04:23.170
[ominous music]

04:23.170 --> 04:26.170
[music swells]

04:27.230 --> 04:30.300
[laughter]

04:30.300 --> 04:31.829
This is where
our alien comes in.

04:31.829 --> 04:33.129
See him coming in?

04:33.129 --> 04:35.269
[laughter]

04:35.269 --> 04:36.800
Ladies and gentlemen,
this is Pickle.

04:36.800 --> 04:40.100
Everyone say, "Hello, Pickle!"
all: Hello, Pickle.

04:40.100 --> 04:42.129
- Pickle likes to help,
so Mr. Jillette,

04:42.129 --> 04:44.029
I'll put your card
right here in his little hand,

04:44.029 --> 04:45.500
and he will hold it
the entire time,

04:45.500 --> 04:48.029
so we can remember the card.
Sir, I have

04:48.029 --> 04:49.800
a bit of an embarrassing
question to ask you.

04:49.800 --> 04:51.500
Are you okay with that?
- Yes.

04:51.500 --> 04:54.769
- Do you have an aversion
for tools that crack nuts?

04:54.769 --> 04:57.199
[laughter]
- No.

04:57.199 --> 04:59.870
- Are you a good nut cracker,
sir?

04:59.870 --> 05:01.970
- Probably not as good as you.
- The hesitation, yes.

05:01.970 --> 05:04.629
The hesitation is not good.
Here we go.

05:04.629 --> 05:08.430
I will take out some walnuts,
just like this.

05:08.430 --> 05:11.870
Now we need to all envision
the letters.

05:11.870 --> 05:13.430
Can we all do this together
as an audience?

05:13.430 --> 05:17.069
Envision the 4 of diamonds,
right?

05:17.069 --> 05:19.000
4 of diamonds.

05:19.000 --> 05:20.430
Let's see...

05:20.430 --> 05:24.470
F-O-U-R O-F D-I-A-M-O-N-D-S.

05:24.470 --> 05:26.430
Miss, if you could just hold
your hand out just like that,

05:26.430 --> 05:30.870
palm up...put that walnut
right there.

05:30.870 --> 05:33.230
Now what we're gonna do is crack
open some of these walnuts,

05:33.230 --> 05:35.569
just to prove that
they are only walnuts, okay?

05:35.569 --> 05:36.970
I know some of you
are suspicious

05:36.970 --> 05:39.500
because I'm a magician.
[laughter]

05:39.500 --> 05:42.129
I'll do the nut cracking.
- That's fine.

05:42.129 --> 05:44.870
Walnuts, right?

05:44.870 --> 05:47.699
You'd be--you reach across
and pick up one.

05:50.670 --> 05:53.399
Have I convinced you
these are just walnuts?

05:53.399 --> 05:54.870
- Yes.

05:54.870 --> 05:57.730
- Aliens are really good
at duplicating things.

05:57.730 --> 05:59.870
This is where Pickle comes in.

05:59.870 --> 06:02.500
Pickle, do your thing.

06:06.230 --> 06:08.170
Did you feel anything?

06:08.170 --> 06:09.329
- A tap.

06:09.329 --> 06:11.329
- A tap.
That's good.

06:11.329 --> 06:13.199
Here, is there anything
in my hands?

06:13.199 --> 06:14.529
- No.

06:31.170 --> 06:33.370
I told you, you thought
this was gonna be nuts.

06:33.370 --> 06:36.370
[audience gasps and applauds]

06:39.829 --> 06:41.199
Thank you so much!

06:41.199 --> 06:44.699
- Anthony Asimov!
Wow!

06:44.699 --> 06:47.100
Come here, Anthony.
That is nuts!

06:47.100 --> 06:48.199
- Thank you.
- Did you

06:48.199 --> 06:50.170
come up with that yourself?
- I did.

06:50.170 --> 06:52.170
Usually I get inspiration
when I'm seeing

06:52.170 --> 06:54.069
other magicians perform,
and I say, you know,

06:54.069 --> 06:55.899
"That's such a great trick!
What would I do?

06:55.899 --> 06:58.029
What would I do
with that trick?"

06:58.029 --> 07:00.870
And from there, you know,
magicians--good magicians

07:00.870 --> 07:03.870
want to do their own magic
and have their own sensibility

07:03.870 --> 07:06.629
and not copy other magicians
and so...

07:06.629 --> 07:08.600
So that's really where I start.

07:08.600 --> 07:11.670
- All right, well, let's get
these guys' perspective on this.

07:11.670 --> 07:13.399
- All rightie.
- All right.

07:13.399 --> 07:16.300
Boys, time's up.

07:16.300 --> 07:18.300
- You know, a lot of people
would think,

07:18.300 --> 07:20.430
people that have watched
a couple seasons of the show,

07:20.430 --> 07:21.470
had learned a little bit,

07:21.470 --> 07:23.100
learn a little bit
here and there,

07:23.100 --> 07:26.470
they would think that somewhere
on the selection of the card,

07:26.470 --> 07:29.100
you would have manipulated
my card selection,

07:29.100 --> 07:31.800
or you would have had a switch
in your hands with the card,

07:31.800 --> 07:33.800
but no, no,
you didn't do that.

07:33.800 --> 07:36.100
The way you had it selected
was very artistic.

07:36.100 --> 07:38.370
Like Picasso or to be more
honest, like Banksy.

07:38.370 --> 07:41.699
You know, it was just fabulous
how the selection was done.

07:41.699 --> 07:44.670
And then,
although you didn't fool us,

07:44.670 --> 07:47.500
I want to judge you
on a higher--

07:47.500 --> 07:49.629
higher plane than as a magician.

07:49.629 --> 07:54.069
You know, because one of the
things I love about performing,

07:54.069 --> 07:56.930
and what I always push for
very much

07:56.930 --> 08:00.300
is for things
to be crazy and eccentric.

08:00.300 --> 08:03.399
So I don't want to judge you
on the--on the magician index.

08:03.399 --> 08:06.430
I want to judge you
on the nut index.

08:06.430 --> 08:11.329
And your alien misdirection puts
you at the top of the nut index.

08:11.329 --> 08:13.269
You were fabulous,
but didn't fool us.

08:13.269 --> 08:14.470
- [groans]
- All right.

08:14.470 --> 08:16.569
- All right?
- Do you understand

08:16.569 --> 08:18.230
what he's talking about?
- Do you mind?

08:18.230 --> 08:21.100
Well, I don't know
if I'm convinced. [laughing]

08:21.100 --> 08:24.699
Where did I specifically...
- He wants you to talk more

08:24.699 --> 08:27.529
about his nuts.
[laughter]

08:27.529 --> 08:30.430
- Okay, misdirection
of the alien allowed you

08:30.430 --> 08:32.600
to gather your thoughts
and get ready.

08:32.600 --> 08:36.299
Then we saw you cop
under the table

08:36.299 --> 08:39.429
and we saw you add in,
as you laid the nuts out.

08:39.429 --> 08:41.070
- Aah!
- I don't want to say more--

08:41.070 --> 08:44.629
- No, and I appreciate that.
I bow to you, sir.

08:44.629 --> 08:46.830
- So now you're convinced
that they know...

08:46.830 --> 08:48.899
- I'm convinced
that this was so much fun.

08:48.899 --> 08:51.700
Love you guys.
- Well, thank you, Anthony.

08:51.700 --> 08:53.600
Thank you so much.
- All right, bye!

08:53.600 --> 08:55.929
- All right, thank you.

08:55.929 --> 08:58.129
We have more magicians
willing and ready

08:58.129 --> 08:59.370
to fool Penn and Teller.

08:59.370 --> 09:01.700
Will they do it?
Come back and find out.

09:01.700 --> 09:03.730
More "Fool Us" coming up.

09:03.730 --> 09:07.730
